deck_excerpt: Bird up is back and it's still as good as before!
deck_description:
Bird Up was the pet name MonoBlueTron's community came up with back during this deck's peak popularity. The deck didn't last long, however, as a key piece to make the two archetypes work together in Lyrilusc - Recital Starling  soon got limited, as well as one of their boss monsters Simorgh, Bird of Sovereignty rightfully so got banned. With access to their omni negate in Mist Valley Apex Avian or floodgate in Barrier Statue of the Stormwinds removed the deck shortly after vanished into obscurity..

 

As of December 2022 however we did see some change. With the new banlist Konami put Recital Starling back to a Semi-limited status, allowing the deck's main combo line to be sort of revitalised, along with a couple of new tricks you can pull off! Scareclaw Light-Heart is a great extender, turning any tri name into ferrijit, allowing you to extend further plays and gives you more options with a properly summoned link 2 to reborn with either Spright Elf or to use as link material with Tri-Brigade Revolt .

Personally I'm not quite satisfied yet with the extra deck and the main deck flex spots. For now I put in board breakers in order to go second, but these can easily be replaced by something more fitting for your locals scene. Pot of desires is also definitely not going to stay when kashtira gets their new support. 

I hope you try out the deck and if you have any ideas or feedback feel free to let me know!

This Krawler-Deck doesn't even try to adjust it's speed to the meta.

Instead we take our time to setup our swarming potential and support it with different token-spells for more link-plays.

The goal is to outgrind the opponent by continuously disrupting his plays with the our Krawlers, forcing him to trigger their swarming-effects and finally beat him with our insec-army.

Honestly you'll probably lose to the meta, but for rogue/casual matchups this deck works pretty well.

Casual Zera deck

NEPHTHYS CARDS
3 Conductor of Nephthys  and 3 Devotee of Nephthys are the main power house of the ritual mechanic of this deck as Devotee of Nephthys can special summon out 1 Nephthys from your deck (You will always summon Disciple of Nephthys with Devotee of Nephthys effects) and can special summon herself back from the grave which is a perfect extender effect while on the other hand Conductor of Nephthys is the card you would mostly summon to cheat out Cerulean Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys from the deck/hand and becuase of that i mostly run 1 Cerulean Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys  on this build. Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys and Chaos Nephthys are also 1 card each and Chaos Nephthys  is mostly an extender that will mostly trigger on the Standby phase where youre Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys will trigger for a massive backrow wipe and will be able to summon itself for more further destruction (This build can fill up the grave with both Light and Dark monsters as we have the Impcantation Engine) and for the last main deck monster of the archetype Disciple of Nephthys it is 1 of the many searchers of the deck and you will mostly want her to search out Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys for a extend fother for Devotee of Nephthys so that she can summon herself back from the field for more extended plays/combos while also triggering our Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys eff for a massive backrow removal OR if you have Sacred Phoenix of Nephthys  in hand you can just pop it and search out Chaos Nephthys instead while also triggering its revival eff. 

The 1st boss monster you would need to summon is Nephthys, the Sacred Flame which is a pretty powerful Tower and is actually pretty easy to summon ut with its full eff due to this decks decent consistancancy. Summoning out Nephthys, the Sacred Preserver is mostly when its a very desperate move as i only put this card in the Side deck when im player an opponent that would actually drag the duel for to long and i was able to win 3 matches with this cards effect but mostly you dont really have to summon her as its kinda rare for matches to drag to long nowadays (I.E Spright and all of that kind of Bullcrap).

ENGINES
The Impcantation engine is pretty simple to explain and there ritual spell (Impcantation Inception) has one of the best reuse eff so that we can ritual summon twice this turn. You want 3 copies of all of the Imp monsters that does not search you out some cards which would be our Impcantation Bookstone and Impcantation Penciplume. 2 copies of the searchers of the Imp Engine which are Impcantation Candoll, Impcantation Talismandra  and lastly Impcantation Chalislime.

The Codebreaker engine is a very convenient engine and you would mostly summon out Codebreaker Virus Swordsman after you have succesfully summon out Nephthys, the Sacred Flame to the EMZ (Extra Monster Zone) and would summon out V-LAN Hydra  to a zone your Codebreaker Virus Berserker  which you be able to swarm the field with so much tokens taht we can use to summon out I:P Masquerena to into Spright Elf and to set our bourd for next turn to either summon out a Link kaiju to disrupt our opponents plays or downright summon another Tower boss The Arrival Cyberse @Ignister. Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax Is the emergency boss monster of this build when your opponent have either dealt with your other boss monsters OR your opponent is player Either Dogmatika or Kashtira which is a massive weakness for many decks and also Accesscode Talker is just there for a OTK tool.

The Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder Engine is pretty self explanitory if you encounter a unbeatable monster just summon out Sky Cavalry Centaurea to Rank-up to Zeus tbh i rarely call out from this engine and it is mostly there a wide better option than going into this play BUT in some of my match i was pin done due to my Boss monsters getting either outed or downright switching sides (I got a lot troublesome matches with Mikanko Infernobles) so its best to include the engine in this build just incase the situation is VERY desperate.

SIDE DECK
It is a bit Budget Friendly with still including some decent removal cards but hey if youre filthy rich and want to irresponsibly waste your money on a card game you could just switch some cards for more expensive and powerful ones.

deck_name: Infer/Noble Knights but it's a Zen Star
deck_excerpt: Built for the Novakin Monthly Master Duel Tournament, with the theme of "Balance".
deck_description:
I continue to attempt to do something with Infer/Noble knights for a tournament, but here I have a bit more restrictions - namely, I have to have an even 25/25/25/25 split of Normal Monsters, Effect Monsters, Spells, and Traps. So that's the reason I'm forcing myself to run the Card Knight and E-Hero normal Mons. I've chosen those specifically because, fun fact, apparently Burstinatrix is the only non-Pend Normal FIRE Warrior monster in the game. And because the tournament has a rule about Normal Pend monsters counting as spells for the purposes of the even split, I've resorted to having the others be LIGHT Warrior monsters instead. Aside from a few Spells/Traps and Monster Effects that fuck with Monster Types, this shouldn't be prove important and I just went with being thematic. Otherwise, this deck focuses mostly on getting Immortal Phoenix Gearfried out on field, then just using him as a wall, cannon, and and also for taking hostages. It is surprising just how many otherwise invincible cards this man can just shove into Equip Spell Prison. Additionally, if Gearfried is already on field or is somehow unavailable, there's also the other Synchros I can use, such as Infernoble Knight Emperor Charles, Ignoble Knight of High Laundsallyn, and even Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying if I'm feeling frisky. And finally, if I somehow brick up but get a couple Normal Monsters in hand, Link Spider + a Normal Monster into either Rasterliger or Ferocious Flame Swordsman is also a serviceable strategy that may buy me time.

Also regarding the name, the "Zen Star" part is a reference to the game VA-11 Hall-A, where one of the drinks is called a Zen Star - a drink that consists of an equal amount of every ingredient, sporting the description "You'd expect something so balanced to taste good. You'd be wrong.". So yeah, describes this deck pretty well.

May RNJesus have mercy upon my wretched soul.

deck_excerpt: Let the Bird fly over you and ritual you too
deck_description:
join the Domain Community and discuss our jank: https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d 
This is a Domain Format Deck - the deckmaster is accessible from the beginning of the game but does not start in place. You are also limited to cards of that deckmasters attribute, type, and name. Singleton format. Multiplayer (3+) 

This is a ritual deck - the core of it is to summon Transonic Bird  to (Quick Effect) send a ritual spell for Shinobaron Peacock  or Shinobaron Peacock. Use their ablitiy to gain advantage, and in the end phase they'll go back to hand, leaving 2 tokens. 
Since we have multiple opponents, on the next opponent's turn we'll continue doing the same thing, (Quick Effect) sending a ritual spell to summon -ShinoBaroness using the Tokens as Material. Thus, you'll be able to use this powerful effect multiple times in one rotation. 
Send: Advanced Ritual Art (uses material from deck), Breath of Aclaimmation, Shinobird Calling

Our Ritual Spell searcher for this deck is Ritual Sanctuary . Field Spell
 
Danger! exists for the draw and high levels. Runick exists for Ritual Sanctuary and lv5. Impcantation is ritual support. Vendread Battlelord  is the backup Ritual Monster searcher. Normal monsters needed in deck for Advanced Ritual Art and in hand for High Ritual Art .Floowandeerze is the emergency button. The Extra deck is fodder for Pot. 

Check out some other powerful Transonic Bird targets that didn't make the final cut: https://yugipedia.com/wiki/Card_Tips:Transonic_Bird

This is an updated version of the previous The Agents I uploaded. Trying out some things a bit differently in this one. Only a bit more consistent but still loses to a single hand trap or sometimes two.

Dark World

Pretty simple, but effective dark world deck

Can build boards very easily.

Most of the time you'll be able to get atleast 2 or 3 power cards (usually a link-4 monster + Grapha fusion + 1 XYZ card (Except Coach King)) on the field, but as always there's still about a 30-40% chance to brick. Dangers getting snipped really hurts your chances as well, to reduce the chances of getting sniped, fill your hand as much as possible (bouncing cards back to your hand for Reign-Beaux/Grapha/Zephryos, Coach King, Saryuja, Number 60 Dugares, Dark world Library, Broww, all net atleast 1-3 card each).

Either way it's a really fun deck to play.

Ideally you want to go first. But it should handle fine going second as it can play through some hand traps.

If you get hit by Abyss, GL (just remember that Reign-Beaux and Grapha effects CAN still be used and don't start a chain!)

Some Notes

  • If you are playing against Tears or similar decks that play in the GY:
    • Swap out one Mothman for the second copy of Dark World Puppetry as this is a great interruption against them (Target 3 in either GY and banish, then discard 1 Fiend monster)
    • Ensure you use Abyss Dweller BEFORE Card destruction, this way your opponent cannot do anything with their discards
  • Coach King is great for winning in time by burning your opponent, and has a great draw 1 (3 times per turn) ability
  • Foolish Burial -> Blackwing  - Zephyros, easy l4 on board and more recycling for your Dark world cards. It's a great extender if you're able to put it in the grave. These 2 cards can also be swapped out for something else if you want

Side Deck

Things you could safely remove to swap out for cards in the Side Deck

  • Card Destruction
  • Foolish Burial
  • Blackwing - Zephryos
  • 1x Dark World Archives
  • Upto 2x Ceruli (although helpful for the handloop and firing off secondary effects, it isn't required for building strong boards)

Extra Deck

I think it's pretty solid as is.

You could swap out Knightmare Gryphon and or Knightmare Unicorn (keep in mind they are Fiends, they give you options while under Muckrakers effect).

Worldsea could also be swapped for Zeus, or something else as it isn't required for this deck, it's just a cool card that I came across as you can summon it using only Appolousa OR Saryuja OR Accesscode

deck_excerpt: Utopia deck, utopia competetive, potential budget version
deck_description:
Why i have 4 onomat monsters and why i play gagaga child? - No, i don't have 4 onomat monsters, i have in total 10 onomat monsters and 1 pot of prosperity. Gagaga Child is important going first because if Utopic Onomatopoeia is negated then i can special summon Bancho and gagaga child from hand by their own effs, so gagaga child is strenghthening the whole onomat engine.

Her effect about conducting battle phase doesn't bother me because going first there is no batle phase, and if i am going second i am not looking for her, my key monsters for going second to help in breaking a board are Utopic Onomatopoeia, Bancho, Armed/Ascended/Zexal construct/Reinforcement and onomat spells. Astraltopia and kuriboh are just boosting the engine with reis map and pot. Even if i have gagaga child in my hand going second it's not bothering any of my combos and is not problem, but the important fact is that thanks to her onomat engine is boosted going first, it's much stronger. 

 

The strongest cards in the deck are Ascended/Armed sage with utopia double because they trigger chain link, that chain link makes cards such as veiller useless because you can chain with utopia double and resolve all your effs.

Important: Zs Utopic Sage is very risky to be played because is easy target for negate and u would end on very weak board if he is negated, that's why i use him in specific combos or in very powerful combos that can withstand negates in the process and make a good board even if he was negated.

Why i don't play utopic future draco? It takes too much space, i need to risk playing zs utopic sage too, the strategy to play draco can't withstand negates in the process so is risky and the board i would have if i play draco is: dragonar + leo equiped + draco + number 38 or 90. 

If i don't play Draco, my board is: Dragonar + leo equiped + abyss dweller + number 38 or 90, i consider that stronger board, i have extra space too and the strategy to make that board is much safer and even it can withstand negates in that process, so competitively speaking i don't need draco.

About Dragonic ray, the most of the players doesn't know how to play him, if opponent succeed in negating utopia double then u can summon in his turn dragonic 5000ATK, if the opponent target him u can either support him with pegasus or either make him not targetable by tornado, it's hard combo to deal with, if the opponent doesn't have card like droplet then he need to use his entire hand to counter all of that.

Utopic future slash + downerd magician are used for ZEUS with 6 materials, yea, Zeus with 6 materials is crazy powerful and is worth it, if u combine it with the board breakers/forcing negate cards that i have in main deck, there is no board that i can't break.

 

MASTER DUEL:

If you don't have Astral Kuriboh then replace him with Brigandine.

I play 3 droplet, impermanence and chalice but you can play mix whatever you have, between Chalice, Impermanence, droplet, kaiju, dark ruler, lightning storm, raigeki. I can't recommend you Ash or Maxx C because these can be played only in your first draw of 5 cards, if you like them you can play them but keep in mind the fact that you can play such cards only in your first draw of 5 cards.

Time thief redoader is used only going second, he is good with Zeus, however, you can replace him with whatever you have, if you want to get something cheap in price but strong then number 89 diablosis is good option. 

 

BUDGET VERSION:

Cut Droplet and you are ready to go :D . U can replace it with dark ruler for example.

You can replace Kuriboh with Brigandine.

You can cut crossout designator too.

Until here i think is enough with the budget version, but if your budget is still low then you can replace number 90 with number 23 or 22. 

 

COMBOS:

onomat monster + onomat spell ///// Onomatopaira + Onomatopickup:

Going first, aim to get in hand Utopic + Bancho + GagagaChild.

Summon Utopic and use eff to special summon Bancho, special summon Gagaga Child with her own eff. Overlaw Utopic and Gagaga Child for Utopia Double and use eff to directly summon Dragonar. Use the eff of Bancho to special summon Utopic from gy and overlaw them for Abyss Dweller. In the opponent turn CHAIN LINK 1 Dragonar and CHAIN LINK 2 Abyss dweller then number 41 is summoned in defense, in that way your opponent can't use gy effs or monsters effs on the field. Note: When your turn comes number 41 is going in gy. After that you can attack with Dragonar and using him you can summon Utopic Slash and Downerd Magician for Zeus, so as follow up you have Abyss Dweller (1 material) and Zeus 3 materials. The Alternative board that you can make is Leo ray equiped + Abyss Dweller and the follow up is almost the same if you need zeus but this time it can be zeus 4 materials or if you don't need abyss dweller then use him for Zeus (2 materials).

 

Dododowarf + Onomat Spell:

You need to discard dododowarf in gy, that's the most important in this combo.

The finished board that you can make is the same as the one explained above in the previous combo. The difference is that you don't play gagaga child in this combo.

 

Onomat spell + Armed Sage:

The difference in this combo is that you can equip Tornado on leo ray or Dragonar. The finished board that you can make is the same as the one explained above in the previous combos.

 

Onomat spell + Kuriboh:

Similar to the combos above.

 

Onomat spell + Ascended Sage:

Special summon Ascended, add Bancho and Utopic, summon Utopic use eff to special summon Bancho, overlaw Ascended and Utopic for Utopia Double = Utopia = Prime = Dragonar. Bancho eff to special summon Utopic from gy and overlaw them for Abyss dweller. By Dragonar summon in your turn Leo Ray equiped pegasus, in opponent turn summon number 38 or number 90. 

Finished board: Dragonar + Abyss Dweller + Leo Ray equiped Pegasus + Number 90 or 38

 

Armed sage + Ascended ///// Zexal Construct + Sage:

In this combo be cautious with the chain links. Eff ascended chain link 1, eff armed chain link 2.

Summon Utopia Double = Utopia = Prime = Dragonar. By Dragonar in your turn summon leo ray equiped pegasus and tornado, in the opponent turn summon number 90 or 38.

 

Reis Map + Zexal Construct/Ascended 

Add Astraltopia in hand by reis map. The difference in this combo is that you can add in hand Onomatopaira as follow up for next turn, if you have in hand already onomatopaira then add onomatopickup. The finished board that you can make is the same as the one explained above in the previous combos.

 

Onomat spell + Reis map: 

Add dododowarf and discard him, keep in mind you can't use his eff but you can revive him by Bancho after you summoned him and Utopic Onomatopoeia and then go for zs utopic sage = ascended = Dragonar 4 material combos...

The reason why i discard dododwarf in gy is because the strategy can withstand negates in this way, but if i have other combo in hand beside reis map, for example onomat spell + sage, in this case when i add dododowarf by reis map i don't need to discard it in gy, instead i can summon him from hand by Utopic Onomatopoeia.

 

Why i don't play numbers protection? - That card is good only when you are going first, if you are going second that card is total brick, the deck is already very powerful going first so i don't need numbers protection, if i play astraltopia with sage i can add by astraltopia onomatopaira, if i have onomatopaira already then i can add onomatopickup as follow up for next turn. If i play Astraltopia + onomat spell then after i summon the onomat monsters on field i will go directly for utopia double and then special summon Astraltopia from hand, i will use eff chain link 1 astraltopia and chain link 2 utopia double,  i am going to add by astraltopia Zexal construct  and by zexal i will get hyper rank up to get to dragonar 4 materials safely, to go for dragonar 4 materials like every other combo utopia double = utopia = prime = dragonar. this combo is solid and can withstand negates in the process too -

- if astraltopia is negated then i can just go directly from utopia double to dragonar 2 materials and use him once to summon number 41 in defense, or the alternative board  instead dragonar 2 materials is to directly summon Leo ray equiped. 

All my combos in this deck are good enough to withstand negates in the process.

 

For going first i have crossout designator with nibiro and ash blosom with called by the grave.

Note: Be cautious how u use reis map, it must be the first card to be used in your turn.

That's enough writing...

deck_excerpt: Tri-Brigade Lyrilusc, a good deck from 2021 which got playable again due to the recent Semi-Limitation of Lyrilusc - Recital Starling!
deck_description:
This deck still can do what it was able to before the January 2022 banlist, and even though it's not a tier 1 deck in Tear 0 format, it can still play against the best deck, thanks to cards like Herald of the Arc Light , which is essentially a macro-cosmos against that deck, and it's really easy to summon, thanks to The Fabled Cerburrel , which is searched out by Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen 's graveyard effect. This deck has a lot of different combos, the three main ones that this list is trying to achieve are the following ones:

- Lyrilusc - Turquoise Warbler + Lyrilusc - Cobalt Sparrow is the standard 2 card combo, which isn't hard to achieve at all, since you need any copy of Lyrilusc - Turquoise Warbler , that is easily searched out by Lyrilusc - Bird Call , and Cobalt Sparrow, which is not only searchable with Bird Call but also sendable to GY thanks to Tri-Brigade Fraktall , which can be searched by Fire Formation - Tenki .The standard 2 card combo leads to Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess with 2400 ATK, Ancient Warriors Oath - Double Dragon Lords , Herald of the Arc light and also Number F0: Utopic Draco Future , with Tri-Brigade Revolt set.

A more complicated line involves Tri-Brigade Oath , and this can prevent stuff like Dark Ruler No More from completely destroying the end board. I'll link the combo that provides that setup: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=991319-45230573

Overall, it's good to see this deck work again, I hope you learned something from this! Let me know if you would change something from my decklist.

deck_description:
Every game you want to draw access to the "Sky Striker Ace" monsters, so playing 10 ways to access them is plenty. These can cycle every turn to gain advantage. The "Bystial" monsters both stops the "Tearlament" deck and provide niche ways to out opponent's boards. Ending on a "Sky Striker Ace - Shizuku" along with some backrow is usually plenty, as it allows you to search "Sky Striker Mobilise - Engage!" which gives constant resource cycling.

Even if you lose the first duel, you can still win game 2 with the variety of floodgates in the extra deck which can be used when going first, and board breakers to beat meta decks in game 3, along with the many going second options in the main deck such as "Change of Heart".

deck_excerpt: Wield the dark arts as master, student, and all of the coterie come together to banish those that oppose them.
deck_description:
As we wait for Chronicle Sorceress to make her grand entrance here in the TCG to join our card pool, we'll just have to get by on some fundamentals for the Dark Magician strategy. Until then, I hope you're prepared to search an incredible amount, take advantage of the summon limit, and control the battlefield with pressure that makes control decks jealous of the hand advantage you can amass (although they've probably got us beat here when it comes to Traps and such-...) anyway here's the rundown of the new Dark Magician line-up!

Pros:

 

  • Snowball: You rack up advantage pretty quickly once you get going with this strategy. Between all of the layers of protection and nuance regarding the disruption lines on top of all of the means of searching from over a decade's worth of support? It's honestly difficult not to win after taking the lead.

 

  • Comeback Potential: Just having Illusion, Rod, Controlling the Dark Magician, or even just having Soul Servant in the GY during mid-to-late game will keep you in the game regardless of how things are going. Just don't play too zealously into something like a Trickstar Candina!

 

  • Rewarding Ceiling: While a lot of the early lines are pretty straightforward, most of the complexities with the archetype as a whole come from the usage of cards in tandem with one another. As opposed to early TCG builds where you kind of just drew cards and hoped it was enough to combo or amass a handtrap/backrow advantage, in Trinity, you'll be much more rewarded for your mastery of the cards at your disposal and how to best navigate the board you're dealt with or expecting. At times the pressure can be nigh suffocating from this deck.

 

Cons:

 

  • Possible to Brick: Unlike its TCG counterpart, due to the nature of the format, DM can't exactly take advantage of so much deck-thinning and draw power and while some cards like the Spellbook engine would help with the cycling process a bit, they will always be setting you a turn behind and adding more additional cards to cycle through in the long run. A brick doesn't necessarily equate to your searchers and passing, it's more of the unplayable circumstances of drawing... all of the Dark Magicians and having no way of summoning them. Hence why we've got some backrow to fall back on and ways to cheat him out in the event of a crisis.

 

  • Bond Between Teacher and Student: This particular list makes great use of Dark Magician Girl and cards concerning her (without playing the Magician Girl archetype of course) and as amazing as the cards surrounding her are, she herself is terrible to use. You'll be wanting to bin her whenever possible or simply control her when under gamestates like Magician's Combination. There's even a cheeky setup concerning Brain Controll (or Big Eye) and using her as Xyz material to go into Dhampir Sheridan. All of those applications aside, she (and her Signature Spell) aren't that great and don't feel that great to have until necessary for certain combos.

 

  • Stat-Checked: If faced with too many monsters that are 3000 ATK/DEF or above you might run into a brick wall sometimes. Mahad can clear all things that are DARK and Apprentice can help the respective targets clear certain thresholds but most of the time those will be one use situations. Fortunately you can use Soul Servant to stack them from the GY to the top of deck for one final use.

 

With introductions over, let's get into the setups you'll want to seek seek more.

 



OPENERS

Thanks to all of the years of support this archetype has received it has gained a number of searchers and retroactive searchers to help boost its consistency and lines of play to be very reliable which is a massive boon when it comes to limited formats like this one. Generally, any starter will net you the same gamestate no matter what goes down; however, there are some combinations of 2 or more cards that do require a bit more setup.

 

  • Manju & Senju: Opening one of these cards enables you to grab Illusion of Chaos (or Sauravis if you already have it) then search Magicians' Souls. Using Souls you'll want to setup your GY with either Mana to protect your plays going down the line or DM/DMG to establish them early and get them in rotation for the later stages of the game. Then you'll pivot into either Dharc or Lyna. With Dharc you can grab Magikuriboh and use it during that same battle phase (or main phase later) to summon a Dark M agician immediately, Witch of the Black Forest if you have particularly greedy setup lines to go for in future turns with fusion plays or revival, or simply Magician's Rod who is the best starter in the deck when combined with other cards in the strategy and it's not even close! As for Lyna, Witchcrafter Golem Aruru will be our primary find; however, Diviner of the Herald isn't particularly bad either. The reason why is below.

 

  • Diviner of the Herald: Using its effect to send, we'll pitch Arc Light from our Extra Deck to make it a Level 6 tuner, then we'll use Arc Light to grab Illusion of Chaos from the deck. Using Illusion, we'll pick up Magicians' Souls and send the appropriate targets like within the Manju & Senju lines to the GY to summon it directly from the hand. Then we'll Synchro Summon itno Fortune Lady Every. This card being a Level 7 who revives itself and answers the board during the SP is very handy for Rank 7 lines and getting rid of pesky monsters. It's worth noting that her banish effect to bring herself back does come up in this deck so don't use it willy-nilly. Banishing Souls is fine, but everything else in this list definitely is not. Use it within moderation as her effect can be used even on turns where she wasn't sent to the GY since it checks during each of their End Phase's. If you happen to need Rod and have a usable S/T at your disposal, you can summon her back, then use that S/T to tribute her and add back the Magician's Rod at EP to start your turn with your primary searcher. Very handy indeed.

 

  • Magician's Rod: This card probably has the highest ceiling regarding its uses since now, with Illusion of Chaos, it can search the entire archetype and its support including adding Dark Magician to the hand when necessary. You may also want to (if on the second turn or later) Link it off into Clara & Rushka so that during the opponent's turn, when you activate an S/T, you can tribute the link to add Rod back to hand. One line I like to particularly setup involves using it as fusion material for The Dark Magicians by grabbing Secrets of Dark Magic, that way in the event that the Fusion would be destroyed and I have a S/T I can use, I'd usually tribute away the Dark Magician girl to recycle Rod for next turn. You can also go for some pretty devastating Bond Between Teacher and Student setups when going second (or later in the game) to nuke your opponent's S/Ts or Monsters. It was this particular line of play that actually winded up getting Dark Burning Magic banned here. Oops.

 

The majority of the time you'll want to stick to opening with one of these cards but if you happen to find yourself opening things like just DM or ways to him, it's still fine to cycle your respective S/Ts and support him as necessary. He's still the star of the deck and it's important to make sure you keep up your advantage until you can snowball the game out of controll.

MIDGAME

This is where most games can end for you since the deck can swarm pretty decently after being setup or be rather controlling between Aruru and Mana being a devastating duo.

 

  • Black Fang Magician: This card can be used to get over some pretty high walls or reach for lethal in addition to floating into cards like Apprentice, DM, Witch, and most interestingly Millennium-Eyes Restrict, The Dark Magicians, and Master of Chaos (unfortunately in the case of Master of Chaos it isn't too great but if you need the banish nuke then look no further).

 

  • Eternal Soul: Don't flip this card too early without insurance, it immediately puts a target on itself and players usually try to remove it when its face-up every time. That said, it can revive DMs for free and search out your one-sided Heavy Storm whenever you want. Use it to secure a lead or establish one. The safest setup to use it under midgame is definitely when controlling The Dark Magicians fusion monster, since if Eternal Soul leaves, the fusion would be destroyed but still float into the master and student, ultimately not setting you too far behind.

 

  • Soul Servant: This card's GY effect is rather potent and is virtually unrivaled when it comes to Unlimited power cards in Trinity Format. You'll usually be resolving it to draw two; however, with this build it's possible to draw up to four cards naturally from this effect- and we play TWO copies. The most important things to note about the stacking (and not searching) effect is that you can use it during the EP of your opponent's turn to rig your next draw and the fact that this card can stack cards from your GY to the top of the deck which is very, very potent in a limited format. Don't forget this as it might save you when piloting the deck!

 


Should the game not end at this point and you find yourself in a complex, mind-boggling gamestate then you're probably going to want one of the following closers.

LATEGAME & CLOSERS

 

  • Dark Magician the Dragon Knight & Eternal Soul: This combination is really rough to deal with, especially since S/T removal is very limited in Trinity, so if this is established you have virtually won. DMtDK is treated as DM so it can be revived by Eternal Soul and is constantly under its protection, additionally, Eternal Soul is protected by DMtDK's continuous effect, making this a really rough situation to navigate for the opponent in most cases. Additionally, since DMtDK is treated as DM, it works with the field spell Magician's Salvation and Magician's Combination so even something like a DMG can represent DMtDK coming back over and over while protecting said cards in the process. This card is a monster and needs to be respected when properly established.

 

  • Magician's Combination: Probably the most underrated support card this deck has at its disposal. You tag out your DM/DMG to their counterpart and negate any card or effect (just not the activation so no Damage Step shenanigans). Once the opponent has had enough and decides to blow up Combination, it even has a revenge effect to clear a card on their side of the field. You can also force this effect yourself with Timaeus the United Dragon and Magicians' Souls turning those plays into removal.

 


Since the lines from the archetype itself are rather consistent, the deck can be easy to get started with, but might take a bit to get used to and master; however, it's usability allows a great deal of customizability to cater to most tech choices like Dragonmaids to establish DMtDK easier or SPYRAL to do Master Plan setups with Magicians' Souls. Regardless, here's a handful of ideas just to throw your way should you aim to adjust this baseline into something more focused elsewhere:

The Eye of Timaeus, Chaos Creator, Magician of Dark Illusion, Noctovision Dragon, Mana Dragon Zimitron, Magician of Chaos, & Chaos Form, Chicken Game, Destined Rivals, and Blazing Cartesia, the Virtuous

As always, if you've made it this far, thanks for checking this write-up out and combing over my iteration of the Dark Magician Starter. Once Chronicle Sorceress arrives you can rest assured that I'll be updating things with fresh lines and even more explosive combos since she increases the deck's consistency by a considerable margin. Until then, we'll just have to keep up a steady pace and recite the incantations of the ulimate wizard in terms of attack and defense.

a fun control deck

Sulfefnir is the best crystron card in the deck, because not only summon itself from hand and gy by discarding 1 crystron card from your hand but after that you have to destroy 1 of your cards, then if you destroy itself you can summon 1 crystron from the deck.

Rosenix is fine because it help get Martial Metal Marcher on the field to get more tuners, but also ust help with getting that extra level needed on the field.

Thystvern is your monster search so not more to say that it's a must at 3 copies.

Smiger problably as the worst effect and that's why I use 3 of it. You want your other crystrons in the gy to use their effects so Smiger can use it's on field effect to get a tuner and maybe get your crystrons from the field in to the gy as well.

Prasiortle summon your crystrons from your hand so like Thystvern it 3 is a must.

Rion, Citree and Quan summon can all summon a monster from different places on your opponents turn and synchro summon 1 machine synchro monster. Rion summons from banished, Citree summons from gy and Quan summons from hand. They can all be summoned with the first effect of your non-tuner crystrons.

Impact is the only crystron trap I use. If you set it you can summon 1 banished crystron monsters and your opponents monsters get 0 in defense. If you have it in your hand you can also send it to the gy with Sulfefnirs first effect.

Scrap Golem is a granet but that's why I like having 2 of them so if get 1 in my starting hand the combo isn't dead.

Scrap Raptor is here for the consistency so it's like you have 6 Scrap Recycler in the deck.

Scrap Recycler is the key card to you're scrap combo, but also it's first effect isn't a once per turn you get to send a machine each time it's summoned.

Cartorhyn the Hidden Gem of the Seafront not only gives you an extra normal summon for a water and earth monster, but can also special summon itself from the gy if you control a water and earth monster. Remenber it's effect says (You can only gain this effect once per turn), this means you can only normal summon once if you want to activate it's effect.

Transmodify can both help get a crystron the gy and get another on the field so you don't have to use their effects.

deck_excerpt: Scrap is a very powerful engine, and combined with the power of Orcust, unleashes a deadly combo!
deck_description:
Deck Overview

Orcust Package:

1 Girsu, 2 Harp, 2 Knightmare, 2 Cymbal, 1 World Wand, 1 Return, 1 Babel, 1 Crescendo, 2 Galatea, 1 Longirsu, 2 Dingirsu

Make sure to use your Orcust cards after you have conducted all non-dark summons, as all the main deck cards lock you into Dark.

Scrap Package:

3 Recycler, 3 Raptor, 1 Golem, 2 Scrapyard, 1 Wyvern

This will be your combo starter, all with the objective of spamming recycler to keep dumping machines.

Other combo-essential pieces: 

Dangers (3 Tsunicko, 2 Jackalope) 

These will allow you to access the full combo, being able to get extra monsters out on the field for link fodder.

Crystron Rosenix and Jet Synchron

Dumps for Recycler to make Wyvern, use Jet if you need to get a card out of your hand like Scrap Golem or an Orcust monster. Use Rosenix if you want to keep your hand.

Lib, the World Key Blademaster and World Legacy Succession

These act as extenders, allowing us to get an extra link 2 that shuffles upon being used as a link summon, which goes great with our I:P.

Generic Strong Link Monsters

In the combo, you will Primarily use Apollusa and I:P for your turn 1 combo, but having all these good monsters that range from banishing the entire field to being nearly indestructible to being a massive ATK monster with a Spell Speed 4 destruction effect.

Other Stuff

Forbidden Droplet

Do I need to explain this, monster negation and getting cards you don't want out of your hand? Major plus

Ash and Maxx C

Also requires little explanation. Drawing 30 is pretty cool and being able to negate your opponents crucial searches is pretty nice.

Foolish Burial

Send monster go brrrrr

Harpie's Feather Duster

Backrow Removal go brrrrr

Combo

 

- Summon Recycler (Via drawing it, or searching it off of raptor and scrapyard) and use it to send one of Rosenix or Jet, use said monsters effect to summon a monster/token.

- Link 2 for Wyvern, use Wyvern's effect to summon a golem. (You need an alternate target to destroy if your opponent controls no cards, so sacrificing a spell/trap or Danger by setting/summoning it before you use the effect. Alternatively, if you drew foolish burial, you can send the other of Rosenix/Jet and use it.) Use Golem's effect to summon Recycler, Recycler then sends World Wand.

- Link with Golem and Recycler to make Lib, Lib then sets Succession. Use Succession to summon the golem, then the golem revives recycler again (golem and recycler are soft once per turns luckily). Recycler sends Harp Horror.

- Link 4 with Wyvern, Golem, and Recycler to make a 2400 ATK Apollusa.

Now here is where the combo can differentiate based one whether you have enough link material. 4 link material is optimal, but the orcust line can only produce 3 without the help of sending more of them to the GY via other methods like return, discarded by a danger, or foolish burial. So I will explain with and without enough material.

 

Enough Material (4+)

- Banish Harp to summon Girsu, Girsu sends Knightmare.

- Banish Wand to summon Harp. The use Knightmare (target does not matter unless it is your opponents turn.) to send either Cymbal Skeleton or Gizmek Orochi. Which will use its effect to summon itself.

- Use all 4 monsters (Harp, Girsu, Orochi/Cymbal's Target, and your 4th monster.) to make Galatea and I:P. Galatea shuffles World Wand to set Crescendo.

You now have 3 monster negates, 1 omni negate that also banishes, an I:P into whatever you deem nessisary which also gives a non-target shuffle when Lib is used for it. An possibly hand traps, Babel, Forbidden Droplet, and Called by the Grave. A very formidable end board, and if your opponent can out it, you have tons of ways to recover that I won't explain here.

Not Enough Material (>4)

Uh oh, this is a problem. Maybe you just got unlucky or messed up somewhere, either way your here, so we gotta do something. There are a few ways you can end you board with only 3 more materials, keep in mind you currently already have an Apollusa and a Lib:

- Make Dingirsu

This offers extra protection while also grabbing a banished machine. But you lose Crescendo, which would be useless without controlling Galatea, you need to instead go for Return or Babel. Which are decent, and it's fun to go for return then draw the fourth summon you needed just before you activated it :/.

- Make Galatea, set Crescendo

This still gives you the omni negation from Crescendo, but you still lose some protection for your Apollusa you would have kept if you made Dingirsu or I:P. You also get crucial spell/trap protection against things like DRNM or Forbidden Droplet.

- Make I:P

This allows you to still access your powerful link monsters and gives you a shuffle from Lib, but you lose spell/trap protection. All it takes is a Forbidden Droplet or DRNM and your board is dead. Whelp, sucks to suck.

These are only 3 of the possibilities, but there are more depending on your scenario.

 

End

Thanks for reading through this essay. This deck takes some skill to master, but though practice, you get a powerful deck that can end on tons of interruption. Or you could get hand trapped to death and end on Galatea and I:P, which is still decent. I hope you enjoy playing this deck, and happy dueling! :)

deck_excerpt: A replica of Zane Trusdales Cyberdark deck.
deck_description:
Unfortunately we only know 35 of Zanes main deck cards for this deck so I had to finish it with cards that he played earlier in the series that seemed like they might fit.

I also added "Cyberdark Impact!" Which was used by Sirus after inheriting Zanes deck and combining it with his own, so since I doubt that Syrus had it I think it's safe to assume this card was in zanes deck.

P.S. I also added a "Curse of Dragon, the Magical Knight Dragon" so that this deck would have a valid target for Instant Fusion, considering the other cards in his extra deck I figured that if Zane were to add a card for Instant Fussion to target it would be a dragon, and there just werent any other good options,
There are only 5 dragon type fusion monsters that are level 5 or bellow, and only 3 of them can be summoned with Instant Fusion, the other two option were "Alligator's Sword Dragon" and "Darkfire Dragon", Curse of Dragon simply has the highest attack from the options available making it the best choice to pair with Cyberdark Dragons effect even if it doesn't exactly fit in with the rest of the extra deck

deck_excerpt: Funny Little Negate Deck Meets Branded
deck_description:
As Drytrons are light monsters, they can be sent to the graveyard via branded fusion to summon Albion. Then, they can be summoned from the graveyard to bring out Herald of Ultimateness. From there, discard fairies to negate their effects as they take a bunch of burn damage from masquerade. Another thing to consider is that Herald of Ultimateness can use any fairy, so did anyone else forget that ALL main deck despia monsters are fairies? Anyways, with the signiture boss monsters from these two archetypes, it should be easy to control your opponent before swooping in for the kill. And if you think there isn't enough control in this deck, that's fine. Just make a variation using Ido, because your opponent apparently doesn't hate the game enough already.

Constructive feedback is certainly welcome here! Thank you!
Made for a 10/10/10/10 tournament.

Alright so basically, if u have enough gas to go into the Roid line starting hand go for it, Search Instant Fusion from Keeper of the Dragon Magic use the field spell to search the Vehicroid fusion spell card, summon Pair Cycroid from instant or if you don't have enough gas from that its a level 5 as well so u can go into nova and infinity. If you feel like your hand is somehow dead go into gear gigant x shenanigans and try to get as many machines in the grave as you can for MIXER ROID, one of the best Roids in the deck, its one of the final gambits in the deck. deck_excerpt: I took Jadens Neos deck from the anime, and removed around 50 of its least useful cards, now it's actually semi-playable
deck_description:
I originally just wanted to do a replica of Jadens NeoSpecian deck, but that has over 90 cards not counting the extra deck so I literally couldn't if I wanted to (the absolute maxiumum amount of cards you can have in a deck is 90 including the extra deck),
So that not being an option I just decided to remove cards until I got a normal 40 card deck and this is what I got!

Anyway considering how many cards there were to chose from I could have gone in multiple directions with this deck, but ultimately this is supposed to be Jadens deck so I decided to include all the Elemental Heros, all the Neo Specians but exclude cards like Chrysalis and most random one offs and went from there, and I think I did a pretty good job of making this at least semi-playable, kind of like the decks from Legendary Decks 1 except with a full extra deck.

P.S. I did not realize that Jaden had a Prisma until making this, I wasn't going to include him at first since he's not that iconic, but he actually really helps this deck since you can use him for Neospace fusions as well

deck_excerpt: A replica of Seto Kaibas Waking the Dragons arcs deck.
deck_description:
Since this deck only had 34 cards in its main deck, and this arc takes place after the Battle Citty arc, I decided to finish it using cards from Seto Kaibas Battle City deck.

I chose to go with The Lord of D. and two Flutes of Summoning Dragon because he is shown having two of them in the battle city arc and this deck could benefit from it he runs a considerable amount of dragons, not just Blue Eyes, then I added Cyber Jar because... well who wouldn't? Cyber Jar is fantastic in any old school Yugioh deck and still has its niche uses today.
And the other two are just filler cards because this deck could use a few more level 4 or bellow monsters to avoid bricking.

P.S. I added XZ - Tank Cannon and YZ - Tank Dragon to the extra deck despite it not being shown in the show because he has all the fusion materials and already runs XY - Dragon Cannon so having XZ and YZjust feels right even if he's never shown to have one.

P.S. While Kaiba does use Mirror Force Dragon, but he uses it while tag dueling with Yugi and uses his mirror force, surprisingly enough Kaiba is never actually shown having mirror force in any of his decks so I'm forced to side deck it.
