deck_excerpt: This lil' Formud Skipper is gonna have a fun day
deck_description:
Domain decks are centered around a Deckmaster who returns to the deckmaster zone instead of the GY/banish/deck when moved.
https://discord.gg/jGkRCJkt3d

In this fun multiplayer format, lets play a deck that uses every archtype's link-1!
Formud skipper can copy the name of any link monster in the Extra Deck, 

COPY Marincess Sea Angel to furfill the condition of "Level4 or lower "Marincess" monster! (climb in link 4)
COPY Magical Muskteer Max to summon Max by condition of "1 Level 8 or lower "Magical Musket"! (accure easy card advantage!)
COPY@ Ignisters! (easy unaffected link6)
COPY Crusadia for the unexpected 3100atk Crusadia Regulex that attacks everything with double damage!

You get the idea! Start every archtype, and play to your heart's wishes!

<> Firstly, let’s acknowledge the @Ignisters! This is a combo line that requires any Ignister or free summon in hand:

Formud > Dark Infant > summon Scrytron > Wickkid (search Bururu) > summon Ignister > Splash Mage > Summon Bururu > Wind Pegesus > Achichi search> Dark Templar > Arrival 

Unaffected 4k attack! Lovely starting setup

<> Let’s go do more, with Marincess! 
No cards needed in hand: 

Formud (add Sleepy Maiden) > Sea Angel (add Dive) > Summon Maiden > Coral Annemone (summon Maiden) > Coral Triangle (add Wave) > Aqua Argonaunt (equip with Maiden) 

Spell/Trap negate and Monster negate! Additional recursion with Coral Triangle reforming Coral Anemone and Sea Angel! 
Go into Bubble Reef the next cycle to draw a couple cards and reborn banished Marincess

<> After that, I’m sure there’s some board interaction that you want! Don’t worry, Magical Musketeers got you covered! 
No cards needed in hand:

* Formud (add Avida) > Magical Musketeer Max (add Desperado, Cross Dom, Last Stand)

Pop any card, Set any atk to 0 + Negate any monster, and Spell Trap negate and destroy! Activate these from your hand! 

<> I’m sure you’re tired throughout the game, let’s just go murdering with Crusadia~~

Formud (add Degrade Buster) > Magus (add Maximus) > summon Degrade > Crusadia Regulus (add Crusadia Revival)> summon Maximus 

Attack all your opponents monsters with 3100 atk, double battle damage! isn’t that threatening? Gain even more attack if your link arrows point to something on the other side!

<>Did you get the combo interrupted? Don’t worry, the main deck monsters are also still one-card combo capable! 
Just summon them out with Double Summon (etc) or try your luck with Reasoning (etc)!

<> Try the myriad different LIGHT options available as well! Chill with Eldlich, entertain with Kaiju or stand your ground with Dogmatika ~~

<> Everything’s finished now….but let’s do it again! Avida, Rebuilder of Worlds can recycle all monsters in banished and GY! Searchable too with Formud! 

Hope you find this fun! see ya!

deck_description:
An old-ish list I whipped up before Tear format that I've made/played in real life. Really consistent, especially if you get Small World and any Hand Trap since all of them are bridges to either Aleister the Invoker or Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous Ecclesia. Pretty easy deck to learn once you have the Small World bridges down (or make a speadsheet), would reccommend if either you or a friend are trying to get into YGO and want something that's decently powerful but not Meta.

Small World Bridges:

Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring -> Droll & Lock Bird -> Aleister (or Ecclesia)

Droll -> Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit -> Aleister (or Ecclesia)

Nibiru, the Primal Being -> Ghost -> Aleister (or Ecclesia)

PSY-Frame Driver or PSY-Framegear Gamma -> Ghost (or Nib) -> Aleister (or Ecclesia)

Aleister (or Ecclesia) -> Droll -> Ecclesia (or Aleister)

TL;DR: Easy deck that gets 3 more Aleisters.

deck_excerpt: Summon everything and draw 12 cards. Have fun!
deck_description:
The deck is simple in theory. Milling Runick Quick-Play Spells (QPS) allows you to turn single activations into a +3. Using the Runick Fusion monsters as Synchro material allows you to free up the EMZ while getting a powerful body on board. Combining these two theories sets up a powerful combo deck that can hold its ground going second too, even playing through interruption. 

The deck has 2 basic opening lines: Raiden and Fabled. We'll start with the easy one. 

Fabled:

What you need: Any Fabled tuner, minimum 2 Runck QPS

Start by summoning Hugin the Runick Wings with a Runick QPS, then, if you only have The Fabled Cerburrel in your hand, discard it to search a copy of Runick Fountain. Curburrel will then trigger and summon itself. Use Curburrel and Hugin to summon Cupid Pitch (NOT to the EMZ), then use its effect to increase its level to 6. Then, activate Fountain and use the other QPS to summon a second Hugin. Chain Link 1 trigger fountain, then chain block it with Hugin. Now for the fun part – use Hugin and Cupid Pitch to summon Chaos Ruler, the Chaotic Magical Dragon and trigger the effect of Cupid Pitch before activating the on-summon effect of Chaos Ruler. All tuners in your deck are LIGHT so make sure to add one of them off of your excavations if you get any. When Cupid Pitch resolves, don't forget to add a copy of The Fabled Abanc from your deck to your hand as it meets the requirement of having 600 DEF. Finally, Normal Summon Abanc then use it with Chaos Ruler to summon either Baronne de Fleur or Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying. From here, you can use any other tuners or QPS in your hand to extend your plays and draw more cards.

For example, if you have a copy of Curburrel in your hand at this stage, you can use Abanc's GY effect to discard it, then summon Abanc, then trigger Curburrel to give yourself 2 L2 tuners. From here, you can activate the 2nd Fountain in your hand before summoning Geri the Runick Fangs, recycling milled QPS to draw 3 and gaining back the copy of Fountain in the GY. Then, use one of the L2 tuners to summon Coral Dragon, then repeat the process of activating a new Fountain and summoning another Geri and use Coral Dragon & Geri to summon the other L10 Synchro monster and draw a card. With the last L2 Tuner on the field, if you have any Runick QPS that you can activate in your hand, summon the 3rd Hugin and go into Herald of the Arc Light. Don't forget to trigger effects as much as possible to maximise card advantage & follow-up plays. 

If you don't open with Abanc in your hand instead of Curburrel, you can make the basic combo by Normal Summoning Abanc instead of discarding it, then using its GY effect to discard the Abanc you search off of Cupid Pitch and summon itself to make a L10 Synchro. 

Raiden:

What you need: Raiden, Hand of the Lightsworn OR Charge of the Light Brigade, any 1 Runick QPS

This combo is far more reliant on luck but has a higher ceiling, however, it usually gives you the resources to keep extending into a powerful endboard anyway. Start by searching Raiden and summoning him (or just summoning him), then use the mill effect. If you milled a copy of Fountain or drew it in your opening hand, you're in a great position. In this case, summon Geri and use its effect to recycle the Fountain to your hand (if applicable). Then, summon Chaos Ruler and immediately use its effect. Ideally, you'll excavate one each of both Fabled tuners or have one in your opening hand (I'll explain what to do if not). Add Cerburrel to your hand and let Abanc go to the GY. Then, use Abanc's GY effect to get both tuners on the field, go into Baronne with Cerburrel & Chaos Ruler, then banish Geri and Cerburrel from the GY to summon back Chaos Ruler and go into Chengying. This is ideal because it only requires 1 QPS to be activated and feild the GY with QPS to recycle for draws. From here you can attempt to draw more cards from the many cards

If you don't mill or draw a copy of Fountain, summon Hugin to search for it, then summon Coral Dragon and Synchro climb into Chaos Ruler to mill + draw 1, then use the card you have to extend/draw as much as possible. Even if you don't end on a powerful L10 Synchro monster, you can still end up drawing many interruptions in your hand and frequently end on Maxx "C". 

If you do have Fountain, but don't have access to the Fabled tuners, the low-effort climb into Chaos Ruler should give you the resources to either deep draw into interruption or into the missing parts you needed to keep extending. The combos here are very versatile. 

Tech Choices:

You might expect to see a LOT of Runick players in Master Duel, which is where Munin the Runick Wings & Runick Allure come into play. Munin acts as great protection in the mirror match with its ability to negate a targeting effect – very useful when your opponent is trying to out your Fountain. Additionally, the discard to search Allure can be used on a Fabled tuner to help you extend your plays. Allure applies a lot of passive pressure in the mirror match as your opponent will constantly trigger it, giving them the difficult choice between outing Allure and outing Fountain (even then, you can recycle it with Geri). Finally, Allure gives you even more opportunities to trigger Chengying no matter what deck you're against. However, I wouldn't recommend Allure in any other Runick build unless you play to constantly benefit off of the discard costs of the searcher monsters as it can often make a winning position better rather than put you into a winning position. 

Instant Fusion is effectively a free Runick Fusion monster that doesn't need to go to the EMZ. This helps you play through interruption and gives you more extension options. Geri will never be destroyed by the effect, so you can keep the extra body on board and give your opponent a hard time if they attack over it. Munin will give you the 1000LP back at the end phase and can be summoned back by Baronne if you used its negate in your first turn as it was special summoned properly. Hugin will send itself back into the Extra Deck. And finally, when Frecki the Runick Fangs is released in Master Duel, it will be able to grab one of your milled QPS from the GY on destruction (Updated Deck profile coming when it is released).

Knightmare Phoenix is a defensive choice against cards like Anti-Spell Fragrence that completely shut down your deck. If you see a card like that activated, use a QPS in response to it to summon a monster such as Hugin, then summon any other monster (usually a tuner) and go into Phoenix to deal with your threat. You might face other interruptions from your opponent, but this is your best shot against blowout cards like that. 

Stardust Charge Warrior is useful for when you need that extra card now and not later. If you have Raiden, Curburrel, and only 1 QPS, you can Synchro climb via Charge Warrior into Chaos Ruler to potentially get the extra QPS you need. Additionally, if you have exhausted many of your options or need to clear the EMZ, you can use a L2 tuner with Geri to get a bigger body and a draw. This can be helpful if you're trying to get Geri into the GY to banish off of Chaos Ruler. 

Tips & Tricks:

Always chose the order of your QPS as you're stacking them on the bottom of the deck – it can come up in grind games and it's helpful to prevent clumping of cards with the same name. 

Always order your chains optimally – usually using Fountain in CL1 and the Fusion monster effects in CL2 is better, but there may come times when the reverse yield better results via either chain blocking or by increasing the number of cards you will draw with worse hands. 

When deciding what QPS to activate to summon a monster, use the ones you run fewer copies of – this makes it far less likely that you'll draw another copy of it to sit dead in your hand. 

When discarding a QPS, discard one you have multiple copies of in hand (or if not, in deck) – this allows you to benefit off of otherwise unusable cards, or prevent cards you draw later from being dead in hand.

You don't always have to combo – while doing a load of plays is fun, sometimes you'll have to take it slow and play as a control deck; chosing the right times to combo and the right times to control will always be rewarding. 

Don't get cocky – always play with the worst-case scenario in mind; you might not draw/mill the tuners/QPS you were hoping for. Before doing something, ask yourself what you can do if a play gets interrupted or a draw/mill whiffs.

ALWAYS attempt to conduct your Battle Phase – your battle phase skip only applies if you try to conduct it; make sure to try when you can so that you can conduct it in the next turn if possible, this will speed up your games.

Activate QPS in the Battle Phase where applicable – once you're in the battle phase, feel free to activate as many QPS as you like; you'll be limited to what you can do here at times but it can be helpful to clear your opponent's board and attack for game a turn early (and even be done just to boost Chengying's ATK).

Don't be afraid to play the long haul – sometimes attacking just isn't viable; your deck has multiple win conditions for a reason. 

Thanks for reading my deck profile and enjoy ruining someone's day on Master Duel!

PS: For some reason halfway through writing this profile, the card search function stopped working :(

Basic train engine with some Kaijus and an average rank 10 toolbox extra deck.

deck_excerpt: Yugi Motos Battle City deck replica.
deck_description:
I have included all the cards Yugi played or was shown to have in his deck during the Battle City arc that are avalable in the TCG, so a few cards are missing,

But otherwise these are all the cards that we know that Yugi had in his deck during the arc.

In order to make the deck slightly more useable I've side decked as many of the les reliable and less useful cards from the deck but it is still more than just a bit bloated.

I've also included Arcana Knight Joker in the extra deck because while we did not see Yugi ever having or using this card, but it would make sense if it did, plus it's a decent extra deck card and this deck needs all the help that it can get. 

P.S. Some of the cards Yugi never actually played, or even had in his hand, but they were shown as being part of his deck in episode 85 when he was deck building, including a good part of the cards that make this deck more playable so I've chosen to include them.

P.S. The two Giant Soldiers of Stone and Magic Formula cards are not a mistake, he was in fact shown to have two of each.
This is the deck that i use on my locals plays, and I like that.

deck_excerpt: Spell economics is back and I guess this is how it came to me
deck_description:
One way or another, "Sky Striker" will make a comeback this format. Regardless of the banning of Mystic Mine and the unphased limitations of the rest of the archetypes cards (Hornet Drones and Engage perspectively), "Sky Striker" is still a top notch challenger for rogue competitions for it's prestige in spell economics and deck resourcing. However the main issue is when your hand becomes your own demise, as it is sometimes known that the archetype jams itself or goes empty handed in the most crucial phases of duels. Hence why there has been a call for both Hornet Drones and Engage to either Semi or Unlimited in recent years in order to combat the ever eroding issues that have been occurring since the end of Master Rule 4. However I am not the one to decide Raye's entire fate alone (and neither is the intellectuals this community has that think they know everything about the game).

 

   "Runick" on the other hand is a nice little addition of the game that plays for itself. Like in previous builds me and many others did, the cards utilize in making annoying effects and banishing top cards from your opponents deck in exchange for your battle phase. How this accommodates with the current state of the game is like taking out a tumor before it spreads, even if you didn't know you have it. As like "Sky Striker" the Mystic Mine ban did hit the deck, but "Runick" took a worst toll as it was their best flootgate option. Regardless, "Runick" builds like the standard and "Spright" variants remain playable to this very day. 

 

   So how does this add up on how "Runick - Sky Striker" came to be? If I have to be honest with you, this is a "Sky Striker" deck that Utilizes in the "Runick" engine. Allowing monsters like Kagari and Shizuku to manipulate your opponents monsters attack much more quickly with the "Runick" spells in your GY. Not to mention the "Sky Striker" quick-play spells being used with Runick Allure to milling additional cards each turn is also a plus. And if you want to get more ridiculous, you could slap in Photon Strike Bounzer to your side deck alongside your Bystial monsters for that monster negate and burn damage.

deck_description:
This is a fun Striker build revolving around the titular Sky Striker cards while controlling the grave with the Bystials!

I am using as many Bystial names as possible, minus 2 Saronir, I want to see at least 1 Bystial per game and the sheer volume of names allows that, You can cut a few if you think it's too bricky

I am running both Triple Tactics and Droplet in the main, Striker is a deck that always wants to go second so you want to run strong going second cards that are also spells to enhance the other Striker spell cards. Triple tact is very strong, an opponent negating anything you do (likely in tear due to Rulkallos) give you a massive boon. Droplet isn't the strongest this format, with most effects occuring in the grave, but is still really good, negating a Kitkallos or a Spright effect is really strong and it can also be used as a chain ender, if you destroy the right card type.

In the side deck, I am running 2 spellbound and 3 Dimensional Barrier. I really like these cards this format, denying fusion from being summoned is super strong and Barrier locks out Tear from doing most plays. Spellbound is definitely worse, but is a spell and can stop link and XYZ plays at the same time, limiting the impact Tear, Spright and the Bystials can have on the field

Other deck choices you can run include Artifact Scythe + Sanctum, or running Twin Twister as apposed to Cosmic Cyclone with Dagda, Metaverse + Necrovalley to lockout Tear even more (personally dont like this option as it stops Kagari from retrieving spells from the grave and screws with the Bystials and Shark Cannon), Kashtira Fenrir (unlike Pankratops, it cant destroy itself, limiting your plays a lot so i dont like this) and a multitude of other options.

Personally, I love this deck and I always love seeing it played. I hope it cant be useful this format, though i doubt it's strengths will be able to stand to the Ishizu Tear might
Have at Thee!!!

deck_excerpt: Imperial Order in the deck master zone, what crimes will she commit?
deck_description:
Sky Scourge Invicil is a very unique card, in that it's both an Imperial Order and Royal Decree on legs.

This deck mainly focuses on playing it as an Imperial Order, with most of the deck being dedicated to interactive traps, LIGHT Fairies that can special summon themselves for free (all the Runick spells are both removal and free LIGHT Fairies which is really nice), and one card combos that translate into big threats without requiring us to activate any spell cards (Tour Guide into Sangan is a 1 card Verte for DPE that searches you a handtrap; Tour Guide into Eccentrick is a 1 card Verte for DPE that puts a light and a dark in the GY for BLS; Trickstar Candina into Lilybell; Dark Contract with the Gate gets you Vice Requiem into Machinex with the ability to pop a card on the field before going into Seven Sins then Zeus; the list goes on). It may look like there are a lot of spells for a deck dedicated to turning them off, but 8 of these are 1 card starters to put a LIGHT Fairy on the board without normal summoning, Fusion Destiny is going to be (hopefully) activated from deck with Verte, which circumvent's Invicil's effect, and Pot of Greed/Graceful Charity are too good as consistency boosters to not include.

Invicil also has some unique strengths as a Deckmaster for Domain format, in that she provides access to EARTH, DARK, and LIGHT (arguably the three best attributes in the game), as well as Fairy and Fiend types, which both provide a number of useful generic cards like the Knightmare link monsters and the Runick package.

Domain is a 60 card singleton format in which your deck must be themed around a single monster card, the "Deck Master". Join the Domain Format discord server and take a look at the rules if you're interested: https://discord.gg/GxXHC4qCYM
